WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:07.360
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab. This is&nbsp;
a free, complete course for the CCNA.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:08.320 --> 00:00:11.680
If you like these videos, please&nbsp;
subscribe to follow along with the series.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:16.320
Also, please like and leave a comment, and&nbsp;
share the video to help spread this free&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:22.400
series of videos. Thanks for your help. In this&nbsp;
video we’ll continue our look at wireless LANs.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:28.000
In the previous video we looked at various&nbsp;
fundamental concepts of wireless networking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.800
but in this video we’ll look at some more&nbsp;
specifics, specifically wireless architectures.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:38.000
By architectures, I mean how the wireless&nbsp;
network fits in to the greater picture of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.240
network as a whole, including the wired network&nbsp;
infrastructure. We’ll cover exam topic 1.1d,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:50.720
access points, 1.1.e, controllers,&nbsp;
as well as 2.6, 2.7, and 2.8.

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:57.760
Here’s what we’ll cover. Before covering wireless&nbsp;
architectures, we’ll take a quick look at 802.11&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.760 --> 00:01:05.920
messages and the 802.11 frame format. 802.11&nbsp;
wireless LANs function differently than 802.3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.920 --> 00:01:11.040
wired Ethernet LANs, so there are some&nbsp;
unique message types and the frame format&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:17.680
is different as well. Then we’ll cover different&nbsp;
wireless access point architectures. Autonomous,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:23.200
lightweight, and cloud-based. Finally we’ll look&nbsp;
at different wireless LAN controller deployments.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:29.600
We didn’t cover WLCs in the previous video.&nbsp;
They are used to centrally manage and control&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:34.240
access points, and are essential in large&nbsp;
networks which can have hundreds or even&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:39.600
thousands of wireless access points. Make&nbsp;
sure to watch until the end of the video&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:45.040
for a bonus question from Boson Software’s&nbsp;
ExSim, the best practice exams for the CCNA.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:53.200
So let’s look at the 802.11 frame format first.&nbsp;
As you can see, it has a different format than an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:59.200
802.3 Ethernet frame. 802.11 frames are&nbsp;
more complicated than ethernet frames,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:05.920
but for the CCNA you don’t have to learn it in as&nbsp;
much detail as the Ethernet and IP headers. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:12.320
I’ll just provide a high-level overview. First&nbsp;
of all, there are many more fields in the 802.11&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:18.800
header than an Ethernet header, but depending on&nbsp;
the 802.11 version and the message type, some of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:24.800
the fields might not be present in the frame. For&nbsp;
example, there are 4 different address fields,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:31.920
but not all messages use all 4 address fields.&nbsp;
Okay, let’s look at each field briefly. First,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:38.560
frame control. It’s 2 bytes, 16 bits, in&nbsp;
length. It provides information such as the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.560 --> 00:02:44.160
message type and subtype. I’ll talk about&nbsp;
the different 802.11 message types later.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:52.240
Next is the Duration/ID field. As the name&nbsp;
implies, this 2-byte field has a few purposes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:58.720
Depending on the message type it can indicate&nbsp;
the time in microseconds the channel will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:04.880
dedicated for transmission of the frame. Or&nbsp;
it can be an identifier for the association,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:09.360
the connection, between the wireless&nbsp;
client and AP. You could say that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:14.560
field is similar to the Ethernet type/length&nbsp;
field, because it has two different purposes.

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:22.640
Next up the addresses. Up to four addresses&nbsp;
can be present in an 802.11 frame.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:27.280
Which addresses are present, and their&nbsp;
order, depends on the message type.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:32.240
The four addresses that can be&nbsp;
present are the destination address,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:39.600
DA. This is the final recipient of the frame. The&nbsp;
source address, SA. This is the original sender.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:46.720
The receiver address, RA. This is the immediate&nbsp;
recipient of the frame, but not necessarily the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:53.280
final destination. And the transmitter address,&nbsp;
TA. This is the immediate sender of the frame,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:57.200
but not necessarily the original sender,&nbsp;
the original source of the frame.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:02.880
Having four addresses like this isn’t&nbsp;
necessary in a wired Ethernet network,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:09.200
but 802.11 wireless networks have unique&nbsp;
requirements. The next field is sequence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:16.000
control. It’s used to reassemble fragments and&nbsp;
eliminate duplicate frames. Then there’s QoS&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.720
control, which as you probably guessed is&nbsp;
used in QoS to prioritize certain traffic.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:30.240
After that is a field called HT, high throughput,&nbsp;
control. This was added in 802.11n to enable high&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:36.720
throughout operations. I didn’t mention&nbsp;
this in the previous video, but 802.11n,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:45.440
Wi-Fi 4, is also known as high throughput&nbsp;
Wi-Fi. And after it 802.11ac, Wi-Fi 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:53.200
is also known as Very High Throughput, VHT, Wi-Fi.&nbsp;
So, HT control is the last field of the header,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:59.200
and after it is the frame body, which is the&nbsp;
packet encapsulated within the 802.11 frame.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:04.560
And finally there is the FCS, frame&nbsp;
check sequence, in the trailer.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:11.120
Just like in an Ethernet frame, this is used to&nbsp;
check for errors in the frame. And that’s all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:17.360
for 802.11 frames. Remember, not all of these&nbsp;
fields are present in all 802.11 messages.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:24.720
It all depends on the version of 802.11 being used&nbsp;
and the message type. Like I said, these frames&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:29.920
and their operations can be much more complicated&nbsp;
than Ethernet frames. If you want to be an expert&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:34.400
in wireless networks you should definitely learn&nbsp;
all the details, but that’s enough for now.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:42.720
Next, before 802.11 message types, I want&nbsp;
to introduce the 802.11 association process,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:45.040
which I only briefly mentioned in the last video.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:51.200
Access points are used to bridge traffic&nbsp;
between wireless stations and other devices,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:57.040
for example hosts connected to the wired network.&nbsp;
But for a station to send traffic through the AP,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:03.200
it must be associated with the AP, and there is a&nbsp;
process used to do that, to form that connection.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:09.840
There are three connection states. First, when&nbsp;
the station is not authenticated or associated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.840 --> 00:06:15.760
with the AP. Second, when the station is&nbsp;
authenticated but not yet associated with the AP.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:22.560
And finally, when the station is authenticated&nbsp;
and associated with the AP. The station must&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:28.320
be authenticated and associated with the AP to&nbsp;
send traffic through it. So, let’s look at a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:34.880
simple version of that process. First, the station&nbsp;
sends a probe request message to learn about what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:40.960
APs and BSSs are available, and the AP sends&nbsp;
a probe response to say that it is available.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.080 --> 00:06:47.680
Note that there are actually two ways for a&nbsp;
station to scan for a BSS. First is active&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:52.880
scanning, where the station sends probe requests&nbsp;
and listens for a probe response from an AP.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.840 --> 00:06:59.120
That’s what I show in the diagram on the left.&nbsp;
But there is also passive scanning, in which the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:05.680
station listens for beacon messages from an AP.&nbsp;
Beacons are sent periodically by APs to advertise&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:12.960
the BSS. Okay, so using either active or passive&nbsp;
scanning, the station knows about the AP and its&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:19.520
BSS. However it’s still in that first connection&nbsp;
state, not authenticated and not associated.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:26.000
Then there is an authentication exchange, for&nbsp;
example the station sends a password to the AP,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.600
and the AP authenticates it. If this is&nbsp;
successful, we have reached the second state,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:37.680
authenticated but not yet associated. Finally,&nbsp;
there is an association request and response,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:42.160
and if this is successful we have&nbsp;
reached the final connection state,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:47.520
authenticated and associated. Finally the&nbsp;
station can send traffic through the AP.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:54.560
Now, all of these messages, probe,&nbsp;
beacon, authentication, and association,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:59.760
are the same type of 802.11 message.&nbsp;
Let’s look at the different types.

00:08:01.360 --> 00:08:06.800
There are three 802.11 message types.&nbsp;
First there are management frames which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:12.480
are used to manage the BSS. For example, the&nbsp;
messages I introduced in the previous slide,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:17.360
beacon, probe, authentication, and&nbsp;
association, are all management frames.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:23.280
There are more management messages than these,&nbsp;
but I won’t introduce them all. The second type&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:29.600
is control. These frames are used to control&nbsp;
access to the medium, the radio frequency. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:36.080
assist with the delivery of management and data&nbsp;
frames. For example, request to send and clear to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:40.800
send messages, which I very briefly mentioned&nbsp;
in the previous video, are control messages.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:46.960
Also, ACK messages, used to acknowledge that&nbsp;
a message was received, are control frames.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.920 --> 00:08:53.840
The third type of message is data. These are&nbsp;
the messages used to send actual data packets.

00:08:54.720 --> 00:08:57.600
Okay, here’s a brief overview of&nbsp;
the information we just covered.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:03.520
I can’t say exactly which information you’ll be&nbsp;
tested on in the CCNA exam, but I think it’s a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:08.560
good idea to have a basic understanding of these&nbsp;
topics. Okay, let’s move on to the next topic.

00:09:10.160 --> 00:09:15.280
First up we are going to talk about different ways&nbsp;
of deploying, of using, wireless access points.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:22.400
There are three main wireless AP deployment&nbsp;
methods. Autonomous, lightweight, and cloud-based.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.120 --> 00:09:29.520
I’ll introduce autonomous APs first. Autonomous&nbsp;
APs are self-contained systems that don’t rely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.520 --> 00:09:36.560
on a WLC, wireless LAN controller. Hence the&nbsp;
name autonomous, they are independent. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:42.000
that means they are configured individually.&nbsp;
They can be configured by console cable,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:51.360
remotely via telnet or SSH, or also an HTTP or&nbsp;
HTTPS web connection via a web browser GUI. For&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:57.040
small networks this is fine, but configuring&nbsp;
APs individually in a large network quickly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.040 --> 00:10:03.600
becomes unrealistic. Note that an IP address for&nbsp;
remote management should be configured on the APs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:10.800
so you can connect via telnet, SSH, or HTTP to&nbsp;
configure them. Radio frequency parameters, such&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:15.760
as how much power it should use to transmit and&nbsp;
which channel it should use, must be configured&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:23.040
manually per AP. Security policies, for example&nbsp;
ACLs, are also handled individually by each AP.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:30.240
Other settings such as QoS are also configured&nbsp;
per AP. And there is no central monitoring or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:36.000
management of the APs. So, as I said before,&nbsp;
each AP is its own self-contained system.

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:43.760
Here’s an example network with autonomous&nbsp;
APs. When using autonomous APs, each AP&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:49.600
should connect to the wired network with a&nbsp;
trunk link. In this case there are two SSIDs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.600 --> 00:10:54.880
so it might be obvious that a trunk connection&nbsp;
is needed because each SSID is mapped to a VLAN,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:55.520 --> 00:11:01.360
but even if the AP provides only one SSID,&nbsp;
the connection should be a trunk. Why is that?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:06.560
It’s because the management traffic used&nbsp;
to remotely connect to the wireless APs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:06.560 --> 00:11:10.320
as well as the other devices, the&nbsp;
switches, should be in a separate VLAN.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:15.840
I might not have mentioned this earlier in the&nbsp;
course, but it’s best practice to keep management&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:20.800
traffic separate from regular data traffic&nbsp;
by putting it in a separate subnet and VLAN.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:26.160
So, there are trunk links between each of&nbsp;
these switches carrying VLANs 10 and 20&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:33.200
for the wireless clients, as well as VLAN99 for&nbsp;
management traffic. When using autonomous APs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:38.800
data traffic from wireless clients has a very&nbsp;
direct path to the wired network or to other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:44.800
wireless clients associated with the same AP.&nbsp;
This statement might be a little unclear, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:49.040
you’ll understand it when you see the path that&nbsp;
data takes when using a wireless LAN controller.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:57.600
So, with an autonomous AP traffic between these&nbsp;
PCs simply goes from PC to AP, among the switches,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.600 --> 00:12:03.440
and then to the other AP and PC. Or between&nbsp;
devices associated with the same AP,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:08.320
there’s no need for the traffic to even go&nbsp;
to the wired network. Soon you’ll see how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:12.240
this is different compared to the traffic&nbsp;
path when using a wireless LAN controller.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:19.280
Notice that each VLAN has to stretch across the&nbsp;
entire local area network. This is considered a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:25.520
bad practice. Why is that? Why is it bad to have&nbsp;
the same VLAN stretched across the whole network?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:32.880
Well, there are many reasons, but here are a&nbsp;
few. First, large broadcast domains. Each VLAN&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:37.440
is a broadcast domain, and if the VLANs are&nbsp;
stretched across the whole network like this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:40.320
each broadcast message will be&nbsp;
flooded throughout the whole network.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:41.360 --> 00:12:44.160
The second reason is that&nbsp;
spanning tree will disable links.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:49.920
A big focus of modern network design is&nbsp;
avoiding spanning tree as much as possible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:56.080
because disabling links means a reduction in total&nbsp;
bandwidth. Also, adding and deleting VLANs is very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:56.080 --> 00:13:02.720
labor-intensive if it has to be done over dozens&nbsp;
of switches in a large network. So, to summarize,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:02.720 --> 00:13:08.240
autonomous APs can be used in small networks, but&nbsp;
they are not viable in medium to large networks.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:09.200 --> 00:13:13.520
A large network can have thousands of APs,&nbsp;
and configuring and managing each of those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:20.000
APs one-by-one is not realistic. Finally,&nbsp;
remember that autonomous APs can also function&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:25.280
in the modes covered in the previous video,&nbsp;
repeater, outdoor bridge, or workgroup bridge.

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:33.280
Now let’s talk about the next major deployment&nbsp;
model for APs, lightweight APs. The functions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:40.720
of an AP can be split between the AP and a&nbsp;
wireless LAN controller, WLC. The lightweight APs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.720 --> 00:13:44.720
handle real-time operations like transmitting&nbsp;
and receiving radio frequency traffic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:49.760
encryption and decryption of traffic,&nbsp;
sending out beacons and probes, etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:56.720
However, other functions are carried out by&nbsp;
a WLC, for example RF management, security&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:56.720 --> 00:14:02.000
and QoS management, client authentication,&nbsp;
client association and roaming management,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:07.840
etc. The WLC centrally controls all of&nbsp;
these things for many lightweight APs.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:13.440
This is called split-MAC architecture,&nbsp;
split media access control,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:19.920
because the functions are split between the&nbsp;
lightweight APs and the WLC. Note that the WLC is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:19.920 --> 00:14:26.480
also used to centrally configure the lightweight&nbsp;
APs. No more need to log into the CLI of each AP&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:26.480 --> 00:14:30.800
and manually configure them one-by-one,&nbsp;
it’s all done centrally from the WLC.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:32.480 --> 00:14:38.400
Note that the WLC can be located in the same&nbsp;
subnet and VLAN as the lightweight APs it manages,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:45.600
or in a different subnet and VLAN. I’ll talk about&nbsp;
different WLC deployments later. Note that the WLC&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:50.720
and lightweight APs authenticate each other using&nbsp;
digital certificates installed on each device.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:51.680 --> 00:14:54.320
These certificates follow the X.509 standard,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:54.960 --> 00:15:00.560
which is the same that websites use to prove their&nbsp;
authenticity over the Internet. This ensures that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:06.160
only authorized APs can join the network, so an&nbsp;
attacker can’t make their AP join the network.

00:15:07.600 --> 00:15:13.200
Here’s an example network, with a wireless&nbsp;
LAN controller added this time. The WLC and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:18.720
lightweight APs use a protocol called CAPWAP,&nbsp;
control and provisioning of wireless access&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:25.600
points, to communicate. CAPWAP is based on&nbsp;
an older protocol called LWAPP, lightweight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:32.640
access point protocol. For communications, two&nbsp;
tunnels are created between each AP and the WLC,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:36.400
like this. Note that each of&nbsp;
those tunnels in the diagram&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:39.840
represents two separate tunnels,&nbsp;
each used for different purposes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:47.520
So, let’s see what those two tunnels are. One is&nbsp;
the control tunnel, and it uses UDP port 5246.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:54.320
There’s another port number for you to remember,&nbsp;
CAPWAP control tunnels use UDP port 5246.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:59.840
So, this tunnel is used to configure the&nbsp;
APs and control and manage their operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:04.560
Note that all traffic in this tunnel is&nbsp;
encrypted by default, so it is secure.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:12.560
The second tunnel is the data tunnel, using UDP&nbsp;
port 5247. All traffic from wireless clients is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:18.640
sent through this tunnel to the WLC. It does not&nbsp;
go directly to the wired network, or even directly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:24.400
to another client associated with the same AP.&nbsp;
It must go through the tunnel to the WLC first.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:25.680 --> 00:16:30.800
Now, of course in reality the traffic does pass&nbsp;
through the wired network to go to the WLC.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:37.040
However it is encapsulated with new headers to&nbsp;
form the tunnel, just like I showed with GRE and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:43.280
IPsec tunnels in the WAN video. Note that traffic&nbsp;
in this tunnel is not encrypted by default,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:43.280 --> 00:16:49.200
but you can configure it to be encrypted using&nbsp;
a protocol called DTLS, datagram transport&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:49.200 --> 00:16:55.200
layer security. I mentioned TLS, transport&nbsp;
layer security, briefly in the WAN video.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:56.240 --> 00:17:02.240
DTLS is basically the same thing, but it&nbsp;
uses UDP, whereas regular TLS uses TCP.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:03.600 --> 00:17:06.960
Now, here’s another difference between&nbsp;
lightweight and autonomous APs.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:12.400
Because all traffic from wireless clients&nbsp;
is tunneled to the WLC with CAPWAP,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:18.640
APs connect to switch access ports, not&nbsp;
trunk ports. You could make a trunk link&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:22.240
if you want, but there’s no need for&nbsp;
multiple VLANs to cross that link.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:27.520
To make that clear, let me demonstrate the&nbsp;
traffic flow when using split-MAC architecture.

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:34.880
Okay, I’ve simplified the diagrams. On the&nbsp;
left we have a split-MAC architecture, with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:41.760
a lightweight AP and a WLC. On the right we have&nbsp;
an autonomous AP architecture, sometimes called a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:48.160
local-MAC architecture. As you know, when using&nbsp;
autonomous APs they must connect to the network&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:54.560
with a trunk link. There should be a VLAN for&nbsp;
each SSID the AP offers, as well as a VLAN for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:54.560 --> 00:18:00.800
network device management. If a wireless client&nbsp;
wants to send traffic out to an external network,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:05.440
it sends the frame to its wireless access point,&nbsp;
which then forwards it to the default gateway over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:05.440 --> 00:18:10.880
the wired network, which will then forward it&nbsp;
according to its routing table. And if a client&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:16.240
wants to send traffic to another device associated&nbsp;
with the same AP, the traffic has to need to enter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:16.240 --> 00:18:21.280
the wired network. The frame is sent to the AP&nbsp;
and then simply forwarded to the destination.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:27.760
When using a split-MAC architecture, this is all&nbsp;
very different. As I said before the AP doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:27.760 --> 00:18:33.200
have to connect to the switch with a trunk, an&nbsp;
access link is fine. However, a trunk link is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:33.200 --> 00:18:40.160
needed to connect the WLC to the wired network. In&nbsp;
this case, instead of the AP mapping each SSID to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:46.160
a VLAN and forming the border between the wired&nbsp;
and wireless network, the WLC takes that role.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:54.480
Traffic from a wireless client is sent to the&nbsp;
AP and then tunneled to the WLC. Then the WLC&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:54.480 --> 00:18:58.800
sends it over the wired network to the default&nbsp;
gateway, which will forward it as appropriate.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:05.440
Even if the traffic is destined for a host&nbsp;
associated with the same AP, it is first tunneled&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:11.840
to the WLC, and then tunneled back and sent to&nbsp;
the destination. Okay, hopefully that helped&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:16.880
demonstrate the differences between the traffic&nbsp;
paths used by each of the two architectures.

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:24.640
There are some key benefits to using a split-MAC&nbsp;
architecture. This isn’t a complete list and you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:28.720
don’t have to memorize it, but you should&nbsp;
be aware of what benefits are provided.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:37.200
First, scalability. With a WLC, or even multiple&nbsp;
WLCs in large networks, it’s much simpler to build&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:43.120
and support a network with thousands of APs. That&nbsp;
would simply not be feasible with autonomous APs.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:50.640
WLCs also provide dynamic channel assignment.&nbsp;
The WLC can automatically select which channel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:50.640 --> 00:19:55.040
each AP should use, so you don’t have to&nbsp;
manually plan which channel each will use.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:56.160 --> 00:20:02.480
The WLC can also automatically set the appropriate&nbsp;
transmit power for each AP, to provide sufficient&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:09.440
coverage without interfering with other APs.&nbsp;
The WLC can also provide self-healing wireless&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:09.440 --> 00:20:17.440
coverage. So, when an AP stops functioning, the&nbsp;
WLC can increase the transmit power of nearby APs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:24.960
to avoid coverage holes. Seamless roaming is also&nbsp;
provided, so clients can roam between APs with no&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:24.960 --> 00:20:32.960
noticeable delay. Another benefit is client load&nbsp;
balancing. So, if a client is in range of two APs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:32.960 --> 00:20:39.840
the WLC can associate the client with the&nbsp;
least-used AP, to balance the load among APs. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:39.840 --> 00:20:46.720
the last benefit I’ll mention is security and QoS&nbsp;
management. Central management of security and QoS&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:53.280
policies ensures consistency across the network.&nbsp;
As I said, you don’t have to memorize this list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.280 --> 00:20:57.600
but definitely be aware that the split-MAC&nbsp;
architecture offers various benefits.

00:20:59.600 --> 00:21:05.440
Now, just as autonomous APs can function as&nbsp;
repeaters, outdoor bridges, etc, lightweight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:05.440 --> 00:21:12.560
APs have different modes as well. First is local&nbsp;
mode. This is the default mode where the AP offers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:19.520
a BSS, or multiple BSSs for clients to associate&nbsp;
with. So, this is the standard operational mode&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:19.520 --> 00:21:27.440
of an AP. Next is FlexConnect mode. In this mode&nbsp;
the AP also offers one or more BSSs for clients to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:27.440 --> 00:21:34.400
associate with, but it adds extra functionality.&nbsp;
It allows the AP to locally switch, to locally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:34.400 --> 00:21:39.920
forward traffic between the wired and wireless&nbsp;
networks if the tunnels to the WLC go down.

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:45.760
So, here on the left are some standard&nbsp;
traffic paths used with lightweight APs.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:46.720 --> 00:21:49.120
All traffic is tunneled to the WLC first.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:50.240 --> 00:21:56.000
But what if connectivity to the WLC is lost,&nbsp;
causing the tunnels to go down? That’s not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:01.200
a problem if FlexConnect is enabled, because&nbsp;
the AP can start forwarding the frames locally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:01.200 --> 00:22:07.840
like an autonomous AP, no need to tunnel the&nbsp;
traffic to the WLC. Okay, that’s FlexConnect mode.

00:22:09.360 --> 00:22:15.040
The next mode is sniffer mode. In this mode&nbsp;
the AP does not offer a BSS for clients.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:15.840 --> 00:22:19.920
Instead it is dedicated to capturing 802.11 frames&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:25.600
and sending them to a device running software&nbsp;
such as Wireshark. So, it listens to wireless&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:25.600 --> 00:22:29.920
traffic and then sends those packets to&nbsp;
packet capture software for analysis.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:31.120 --> 00:22:37.840
The next mode is Monitor mode. Again, it doesn’t&nbsp;
offer a BSS for clients. Instead it is dedicated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:37.840 --> 00:22:44.720
to receiving 802.11 frames to detect rogue&nbsp;
devices. If a client is found to be a rogue&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:44.720 --> 00:22:50.800
device, an AP can send de-authentication messages&nbsp;
to disassociate the rogue device from the AP.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:58.400
The next mode, rogue detector mode, is similar&nbsp;
but different in a key way. In this mode the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:58.400 --> 00:23:04.240
AP does not even use its radio. Instead it&nbsp;
listens to traffic on the wired network only,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:04.240 --> 00:23:11.600
but it receives a list of suspected rogue clients&nbsp;
and AP MAC addresses from the WLC. By listening to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:17.200
ARP messages on the wired network and correlating&nbsp;
it with the information it receives from the WLC,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:17.920 --> 00:23:24.400
it can detect rogue devices. Okay, the next is&nbsp;
yet another mode that does not offer a BSS for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:32.880
clients. That is SE-connect, or spectrum expert&nbsp;
connect. In this mode the AP is dedicated to RF&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:32.880 --> 00:23:38.880
spectrum analysis on all channels. It can send&nbsp;
information to software such as Cisco Spectrum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:38.880 --> 00:23:45.200
Expert on a PC to collect and analyze the data.&nbsp;
This can help find sources of interference.

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:49.840
Okay, the next mode is bridge/mesh mode.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:56.160
Like the autonomous AP’s outdoor bridge mode,&nbsp;
the lightweight AP can be a dedicated bridge&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:56.160 --> 00:24:02.240
between sites, even over long distances. A mesh&nbsp;
can also be made between the access points.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.440 --> 00:24:08.560
Here’s an example similar to what we saw in the&nbsp;
previous video, APs connecting sites together.

00:24:10.080 --> 00:24:14.320
And here’s an example that looks more like&nbsp;
a mesh, again connecting sites together over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:14.320 --> 00:24:20.560
potentially long distances. Now there’s&nbsp;
one more mode. That is flex plus bridge,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:26.400
which basically adds flexconnect functionality&nbsp;
to the bridge/mesh mode. This allows wireless&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:31.840
access points to locally forward traffic&nbsp;
even if connectivity to the WLC is lost.

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:37.840
Here’s that complete list. This is a lot&nbsp;
of different modes and we only very briefly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:37.840 --> 00:24:43.440
looked at each one, but that’s okay. If you&nbsp;
want to know more about any of these modes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:48.080
Cisco has documentation about each of them&nbsp;
and you can find it with a Google search,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:53.360
but for the CCNA exam you should just be able to&nbsp;
identify the basic purpose of each of these modes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:54.320 --> 00:24:59.840
I don’t recommend memorizing this list,&nbsp;
just understand the basic purpose of each.

00:25:00.880 --> 00:25:06.960
Now let’s look at the last main type of AP&nbsp;
architecture, cloud-based. Cloud-based AP&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:06.960 --> 00:25:12.640
architecture is in between autonomous AP and&nbsp;
split-MAC architecture, in terms of how it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:12.640 --> 00:25:19.280
functions. Basically, it involves autonomous&nbsp;
APs that are centrally managed in the cloud.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:20.160 --> 00:25:26.000
An example is Cisco Meraki, and because the&nbsp;
CCNA is a Cisco exam that’s probably the one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:32.160
you should be aware of for the CCNA. The Meraki&nbsp;
dashboard, which is a website you login to,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:32.720 --> 00:25:37.600
can be used to configure APs, monitor the&nbsp;
network, generate performance reports,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:37.600 --> 00:25:44.960
etc. Just like I mentioned for WLCs, Meraki&nbsp;
also tells each AP which channel to use,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:44.960 --> 00:25:51.200
what transmit power to use, etc. However,&nbsp;
regular data traffic is not sent to the cloud.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:51.840 --> 00:25:56.320
It is sent directly to the wired&nbsp;
network like when using autonomous APs.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:56.320 --> 00:26:01.200
So, only what we call management traffic&nbsp;
or control traffic is sent to the cloud.

00:26:02.400 --> 00:26:08.960
Let’s see an example. Information such as RF&nbsp;
spectrum information and management information&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:08.960 --> 00:26:14.160
is sent to servers in the Meraki cloud.&nbsp;
But regular data traffic, such as two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:19.200
PCs communicating with each other, is direct and&nbsp;
there is no need for it to be sent to the cloud.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:25.440
So, I think you can see how the functionality&nbsp;
is in between autonomous and lightweight APs.

00:26:27.280 --> 00:26:33.680
Here’s an image from Meraki demonstrating the same&nbsp;
concept. Notice that the Meraki management data,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:39.920
the green arrow, is sent to the Meraki cloud.&nbsp;
However, user data, so regular traffic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.920 --> 00:26:44.880
is sent directly to its intended destination&nbsp;
such as a web server or a file server.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:50.880
Here’s another image from that same Meraki&nbsp;
webpage, giving a look at the Meraki dashboard.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:51.680 --> 00:26:56.720
This is where you monitor the wireless network,&nbsp;
make configuration changes to APs, etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:57.920 --> 00:27:03.520
I use the Cisco Meraki solution in my job and&nbsp;
I really like it. It’s easy to use and set up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:08.880
and the Meraki dashboard makes it easy to monitor&nbsp;
the wireless network and make changes as needed.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:14.480
Okay, that’s all for the cloud-based&nbsp;
architecture. Like I said, it’s halfway&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:20.480
between autonomous AP and split-MAC architecture.&nbsp;
Autonomous APs that are centrally managed.

00:27:22.640 --> 00:27:28.560
The final topic for today is WLC deployment&nbsp;
models. Since we’re talking about wireless&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:32.720
LAN controllers, this applies&nbsp;
to split-MAC architecture only,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:32.720 --> 00:27:40.080
not autonomous AP or cloud-based AP architectures.&nbsp;
There are four main WLC deployment models,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:40.080 --> 00:27:46.320
four ways to deploy a WLC in your network. I’ll&nbsp;
show each one with a diagram, but let’s summarize&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:46.320 --> 00:27:54.240
them first. First, a unified WLC deployment. The&nbsp;
WLC is a hardware appliance, a separate hardware&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:54.240 --> 00:28:00.640
device, in a central location of the network.&nbsp;
Then there is the cloud-based WLC deployment.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:01.200 --> 00:28:06.400
The WLC is a VM running on a server,&nbsp;
usually in a private cloud in a data center.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:07.280 --> 00:28:11.840
Keep in mind that this is not the same as the&nbsp;
cloud-based AP architecture we just discussed.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:12.800 --> 00:28:19.040
In this case the APs are not cloud-based, they&nbsp;
are lightweight APs. The ‘Cloud-based’ named&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:19.040 --> 00:28:28.320
here simply refers to where the WLC is. In an&nbsp;
embedded WLC deployment, the WLC is integrated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:28.320 --> 00:28:33.520
in a switch in the network. And finally&nbsp;
in a Cisco Mobility Express deployment,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:34.080 --> 00:28:39.840
the WLC functionality is actually integrated&nbsp;
within one or more of the APs in the network.

00:28:41.920 --> 00:28:47.920
So here is an example of a unified WLC, a&nbsp;
separate device, a separate hardware appliance,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:55.040
that is deployed in a central location of the&nbsp;
network. A unified WLC can support up to about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:55.040 --> 00:29:02.000
6000 APs, and if you need more than that you can&nbsp;
add additional WLCs. This kind of deployment is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:08.240
suitable for a large enterprise campus. Here’s&nbsp;
a photo of some different Cisco WLC models.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:13.680
Of course the larger models are more powerful&nbsp;
and can support more APs than the smaller ones.

00:29:15.120 --> 00:29:22.080
Next is the cloud-based WLC. In this case the&nbsp;
WLC is a VM running on a server, typically in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:22.080 --> 00:29:29.280
a private cloud in a data center. This kind of&nbsp;
WLC can typically support up to about 3000 APs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:29.280 --> 00:29:35.440
and again if more are needed you can add&nbsp;
more WLC VMs. I’d like to repeat here that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:35.440 --> 00:29:41.200
a split-MAC architecture with a cloud-based WLC&nbsp;
is different than the cloud-based AP deployment&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:41.200 --> 00:29:47.840
we looked at earlier. These are lightweight APs,&nbsp;
and cloud-based just refers to where the WLC is.

00:29:49.840 --> 00:29:55.120
Next, embedded WLCs. In this case&nbsp;
the WLC is embedded within a switch.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:56.080 --> 00:30:01.760
This type of WLC can support up to about 200&nbsp;
APs, and if you need more you’ll have to add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:01.760 --> 00:30:07.840
more switches with embedded WLCs. Embedded&nbsp;
WLCs are suitable for smaller campuses.

00:30:09.440 --> 00:30:18.000
Finally, Cisco Mobility Express places the WLC&nbsp;
within an AP. The AP containing the WLC builds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:25.520
internal CAPWAP tunnels to it, and the other&nbsp;
APs do too. A mobility express WLC can support&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:25.520 --> 00:30:32.080
up to about 100 APs, and you’ll have to add&nbsp;
more APs with embedded mobility express WLCs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:32.080 --> 00:30:37.360
to support more APs. This kind of deployment&nbsp;
is suitable for a small branch office.

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:42.320
Here’s that summary of the&nbsp;
different WLC deployment models,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:42.320 --> 00:30:45.840
and I’ve added information about how&nbsp;
many APs can be supported by each.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:46.720 --> 00:30:49.840
Definitely be familiar with these&nbsp;
four deployment types for the exam.

00:30:52.080 --> 00:30:56.800
Okay, here’s what we covered in this video.&nbsp;
We started with a brief introduction to some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:56.800 --> 00:31:03.840
different kinds of 802.11 messages and the&nbsp;
frame format used by 802.11 wireless frames.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:04.400 --> 00:31:08.320
Because wireless networks have different&nbsp;
requirements than wired networks,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:08.320 --> 00:31:14.640
there are quite a few differences between 802.3&nbsp;
Ethernet frames and 802.11 wireless frames.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:15.520 --> 00:31:21.840
We then covered the three main kinds of APs,&nbsp;
autonomous, lightweight, and cloud-based. Make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:21.840 --> 00:31:27.520
sure you know the basic characteristics of each&nbsp;
and are able to compare them. Finally we looked at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:31.840
the different wireless LAN controller deployment&nbsp;
options to be used with lightweight APs.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:32.960 --> 00:31:36.160
Make sure to watch until the end&nbsp;
of the quiz for a bonus practice&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:41.760
question from Boson Software’s ExSim for&nbsp;
CCNA. Okay, let’s go to quiz question 1.

00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:50.720
What kind of message is an 802.11 probe request?&nbsp;
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:31:55.520 --> 00:32:02.000
Okay, the answer is C, management. Here are&nbsp;
those 802.11 message types we covered earlier,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:05.920
with a few examples of each.&nbsp;
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.800
Which of the following AP&nbsp;
types are centrally managed?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:11.360 --> 00:32:14.480
Pause the video now to select&nbsp;
the best answer, select two.

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:22.080
Okay, the answers are C, lightweight, and D,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:22.080 --> 00:32:29.040
cloud-based. Lightweight APs are centrally managed&nbsp;
by a wireless LAN controller, and cloud-based APs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:29.040 --> 00:32:34.960
are centrally managed by a cloud server such&nbsp;
as Cisco Meraki. Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:32:37.520 --> 00:32:41.520
Which of the following AP&nbsp;
types uses the CAPWAP protocol?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:41.520 --> 00:32:43.840
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:32:48.480 --> 00:32:55.280
Okay, the answer is C, lightweight. Lightweight&nbsp;
APs use CAPWAP to communicate with the WLC via&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:55.280 --> 00:33:00.880
two tunnels, a control tunnel and a data&nbsp;
tunnel. Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:07.920
Which of the following lightweight&nbsp;
AP modes offer a BSS for clients?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:08.640 --> 00:33:11.440
Pause the video to select&nbsp;
the best answers, select two.

00:33:15.600 --> 00:33:22.320
Okay, the answers are A, local and C, flexconnect.&nbsp;
Local is the default standard operating mode.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:28.000
FlexConnect offers the additional ability&nbsp;
to continue forwarding data traffic locally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:32.880
even if the tunnels to the WLC go&nbsp;
down. Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:33:36.160 --> 00:33:40.400
Which of the following WLC deployments&nbsp;
supports the greatest number of APs?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:41.040 --> 00:33:43.360
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:33:47.760 --> 00:33:56.080
Okay, the answer is D, unified. Embedded WLCs&nbsp;
support about 200 APs, cloud-based about 3000,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:56.080 --> 00:34:02.400
mobility express about 100, and unified&nbsp;
about 6000. Okay, that’s all for the quiz.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:08.033
Now let’s take a look at a bonus practice&nbsp;
question from Boson Software’s ExSim for CCNA.

